                    1. Introduction to Cat Care
                </p>
                <p class="mainText">
                    Cats are beloved companions known for their independent nature, but they still require attention and proper care. As a pet owner, it's important to provide your cat with the right environment, nutrition, grooming, and medical care to ensure they lead a healthy, happy life. Cats may appear self-sufficient, but they thrive on interaction, routine, and affection. Understanding the basic needs of cats will help you form a strong bond with your feline friend and ensure their well-being.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="mainColor2">
                <p class="secondaryTextTitle">
                    2. Providing a Healthy Diet
                </p>
                <p class="mainText">
                    A balanced and nutritious diet is fundamental to your catâ€™s health. Cats are obligate carnivores, meaning they require animal-based proteins to thrive. Ensure your cat is fed high-quality commercial food, such as wet or dry food, or a mix of both, that meets their nutritional needs. Additionally, fresh water should always be available, as dehydration can lead to health issues. Avoid feeding your cat human food, particularly toxic items like chocolate, onions, or grapes. Special dietary considerations may be necessary for cats with health conditions, so consult with a veterinarian if you're unsure about the best food for your cat.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div>
                <p class="secondaryTextTitle">
                    3. Grooming and Hygiene
                </p>
                <p class="mainText">
                    Regular grooming is essential to keep your cat's coat in good condition. Long-haired cats require more frequent brushing to prevent matting, while short-haired cats need occasional brushing to reduce shedding and hairballs. Cats are generally very clean, but they will still appreciate assistance in keeping their fur free from tangles. Additionally, be sure to clean their litter box daily to maintain hygiene and prevent any odors. Nail trimming and ear cleaning are also part of basic grooming, though not all cats will tolerate these procedures. A calm, patient approach will help make grooming sessions more enjoyable for both you and your cat.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="mainColor1">
                <p class="secondaryTextTitle">
                    4. Regular Veterinary Care
                </p>
                <p class="mainText">
                    Routine veterinary visits are essential to keeping your cat healthy. Vaccinations, flea prevention, and regular check-ups will help detect any early signs of illness, and preventative care can reduce the risk of serious conditions. Spaying or neutering your cat is also recommended to prevent unwanted behaviors and health issues. Cats may be good at hiding symptoms of illness, so being proactive with veterinary care can help catch any potential problems before they become more serious.
                </p>
            </div>
